   "source": [
    "#| tbl-cap: Activity Measures and Descriptive Statistics for the three stocks (AstraZeneca, Next, and Burberry).\n",
    "# compact headline table, including activity measures\n",
    "headline = pd.DataFrame({s: {\n",
    "    \"Avg spread (bps)\":      df[df.Stock == s][\"Spread_bps\"].mean(),\n",
    "    \"Median spread (bps)\":   df[df.Stock == s][\"Spread_bps\"].median(),\n",
    "    \"Avg depth (GBP)\":       df[df.Stock == s][\"Depth\"].mean(),\n",
    "    \"Avg |1-min ret| (bps)\": df[df.Stock == s][\"Ret_bps\"].abs().mean(),\n",
    "    \"Avg trades / min\":      df[df.Stock == s][\"Num. Trades\"].mean(),\n",
    "    \"% minutes traded\":      100 * (df[df.Stock == s][\"Num. Trades\"].fillna(0) > 0).mean(),\n",
    "} for s in chosen_stocks}).round(2)\n",
    "headline"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "17492a2d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The rankings depicted are consistent; AZN.L is the most liquid with the tightest spread (approx 2.5 basis points) and the most active trading, as suspected. BRBY.L is the least liquid with a spread of approximately 14 basis points and much thinner depth. This matches the pattern that the larger, more active stocks are therefore easier to trade and ultimately cheaper than the smaller ones. Therefore, the cost and the size of the stocks are interrelated.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Intraday Liquidity Patterns\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we average each measure by time of day across all 64 days, which isolates the typical shape of the trading day. We look at spread, depth and volume."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "ca0df35c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 4500x1050 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#| fig-cap: Left to right; Average Depth by Time of Day, and Average Volume by Time of Day.\n",
    "# Bin timestamps to a coarser interval (e.g. 15 min) before aggregating\n",
    "\n",
    "BIN = \"15min\"   # try \"5min\", \"10min\", \"15min\", \"30min\"\n",
    "df[\"TimeBin\"] = df[\"Date and time\"].dt.floor(BIN).dt.strftime(\"%H:%M\")\n",
    "\n",
    "intraday = (df.groupby([\"Stock\", \"TimeBin\"])\n",
    "              .agg(Spread_bps=(\"Spread_bps\", \"mean\"),\n",
    "                   Depth=(\"Depth\", \"mean\"),\n",
    "                   Volume=(\"Volume\", lambda s: s.fillna(0).mean()))\n",
    "              .reset_index())\n",
    "\n",
    "panels = [(\"Depth\",      \"Average depth (GBP)\"),\n",
    "          (\"Volume\",     \"Average volume (shares)\")]\n",
    "\n",
    "times = sorted(intraday[\"TimeBin\"].unique())\n",
    "step = max(1, len(times) // 10)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a single figure with 1 row and 2 columns\n",
    "# Increased figsize width to 16 to accommodate both plots comfortably side-by-side\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 3.5)) \n",
    "\n",
    "# zip(axes, panels) pairs the first axis with \"Depth\", and the second with \"Volume\"\n",
    "for ax, (col, ylabel) in zip(axes, panels):\n",
    "    for s in chosen_stocks:\n",
    "        sub = intraday[intraday[\"Stock\"] == s].set_index(\"TimeBin\").reindex(times).reset_index()\n",
    "        ax.plot(sub[\"TimeBin\"], sub[col], color=COLOURS[s], label=s, linewidth=1.3)\n",
    "        \n",
    "    ax.set_title(f\"{ylabel} by time of day\")\n",
    "    ax.set_xlabel(\"Time of day\")\n",
    "    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)\n",
    "    ax.set_xticks(range(0, len(times), step))\n",
    "    ax.set_xticklabels(times[::step], rotation=45)\n",
    "    ax.legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
