   ],
   "source": [
    "#| fig-cap: 'Intraday day spread buckets; Left to Right: AstraZeneca, Next, and Burberry.'\n",
    "# 30-minute spread buckets, one panel per stock, to show the level differences clearly\n",
    "df[\"Bucket\"] = df[\"Date and time\"].dt.floor(\"30min\").dt.strftime(\"%H:%M\")\n",
    "bucket_spread = (df.groupby([\"Stock\", \"Bucket\"])\n",
    "                   .agg(Avg_Spread=(\"Spread_bps\", \"mean\")).reset_index())\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 3.5))\n",
    "for i, s in enumerate(chosen_stocks):\n",
    "    sub = bucket_spread[bucket_spread[\"Stock\"] == s]\n",
    "    axes[i].bar(sub[\"Bucket\"], sub[\"Avg_Spread\"], color=COLOURS[s], edgecolor=\"white\", linewidth=0.4)\n",
    "    axes[i].set_title(s); axes[i].set_xlabel(\"Time of day\")\n",
    "    axes[i].tick_params(axis=\"x\", rotation=45)\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel(\"Average spread (bps)\")\n",
    "fig.suptitle(\"Intraday spread pattern by stock\", fontweight=\"bold\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "573593fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The shape is the same for all three stocks, only the level differs. Spreads are widest right after the open, when there is still uncertainty from overnight news and the book is thin, and they tighten steadily as the session goes on. Depth moves the other way: it is lowest at the open and builds up through the day, reaching its highest level into the close. The decline in spreads continues all the way into the close rather than turning back up, which fits the way liquidity concentrates around the closing auction on the LSE. As described per @Mcinish1992, this pattern is consistent with the idea that information is progressive.\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the takeaway is to avoid sending large or cost-sensitive orders in the first 30 to 45 minutes, and to lean on the deeper, cheaper later part of the day. The penalty for trading at the open is largest in the least liquid name, Burberry, whose opening spread is both the widest and the most elevated relative to its own daily average.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Daily Liquidity & Volatility\n",
    "\n",
    "The brief defines **daily volatility** as the mean of the absolute one-minute mid-quote returns within a day:\n",
    "$$\\sigma_d = \\frac{1}{N_d}\\sum_{t \\in d} |r_t|$$\n",
    "We aggregate the minute-level data to one observation per stock-day, then study how daily spread relates to daily volatility using correlations and an OLS regression."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "7810b373",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
