     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 3.5))\n",
    "for ax, s in zip(axes, chosen_stocks):\n",
    "    sub = daily[daily[\"Stock\"] == s]\n",
    "    x, y = sub[\"Daily_Volatility\"].values, sub[\"Daily_Spread\"].values\n",
    "    ax.scatter(x, y, color=COLOURS[s], alpha=0.7, edgecolor=\"white\", linewidth=0.5)\n",
    "    b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)\n",
    "    xs = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), 100)\n",
    "    ax.plot(xs, np.polyval(b, xs), color=\"black\", linestyle=\"--\", linewidth=1.5)\n",
    "    r = stats.pearsonr(x, y)[0]\n",
    "    ax.set_title(f\"{s}   (r = {r:+.2f})\")\n",
    "    ax.set_xlabel(\"Daily volatility (mean |1-min ret|, bps)\")\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel(\"Daily spread (bps)\")\n",
    "fig.suptitle(\"Daily spread vs daily volatility\", fontweight=\"bold\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "59851455",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Reading the Scatter Plots\n",
    "\n",
    "For every stock the points slope upward and the fitted line is positive, so days with higher volatility tend to have wider spreads. The slope is gentlest for AstraZeneca and steepest for Burberry, which means the small-cap's trading cost reacts the most to volatility. We put numbers on these slopes in the regression below.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Regression Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "For each stock we regress daily spread on daily volatility:\n",
    "$$\\text{Daily Spread}_d = \\alpha + \\beta \\cdot \\sigma_d + \\varepsilon_d$$\n",
    "A positive $\\beta$ means higher volatility goes with wider spreads, i.e. lower liquidity. We use HC1 heteroskedasticity-robust standard errors, since the size of the regression errors is likely to vary with volatility."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "3a640d6f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
